{
    "title": "DOJ: Ferguson PD engaged in racially biased policing",
    "news": [
        {
            "id": 1,
            "text": "A Justice Department review has found that Missouri's troubled Ferguson Police Department engaged in a broad pattern of racially biased enforcement that permeated the city's justice system, including the use of unreasonable force against African American suspects, according to a law enforcement official familiar with the findings."
        },
        {
            "id": 2,
            "text": "In 88% of cases in which Ferguson police documented the use of force, for example, that force was used against African Americans, according to the official who is not authorized to comment publicly."
        },
        {
            "id": 3,
            "text": "In addition, in all 14 canine bite incidents in which the suspect's race is known, the person bitten was African American."
        },
        {
            "id": 4,
            "text": "African Americans account for 67% of the population in Ferguson, but they accounted for 85% of the drivers stopped by police, 90% of the people issued tickets and 93% of the people arrested, a three-year examination of suspect stops found."
        },
        {
            "id": 5,
            "text": "When those cases reached the Municipal Court, authorities collected more fines for suspects' failure to appear than any other charge, mostly from the city's poorest and most vulnerable residents."
        },
        {
            "id": 6,
            "text": "African Americans were more than twice as likely than white drivers to be searched during vehicle stops, but 26% less likely to have contraband, the review found."
        },
        {
            "id": 7,
            "text": "The Ferguson Police Department often charged its black residents with petty crimes."
        },
        {
            "id": 8,
            "text": "African Americans accounted for 95% of the people charged with walking in the street and 92% of people charged with disturbing the peace."
        },
        {
            "id": 9,
            "text": "Investigators also recovered racially charged e-mails sent among employees of the police department and the Ferguson Municipal Court, which authorities said contributed to the alleged bias."
        },
        {
            "id": 10,
            "text": "Among the e-mails was a missive apparently sent soon after President Obama's 2008 election."
        },
        {
            "id": 11,
            "text": "It suggested that he would not remain long in the job because \"what black man holds a steady job for four years.''"
        },
        {
            "id": 12,
            "text": "Another May 2011 e-mail referred to an African-American woman receiving a \"Crime-stoppers'' reward for terminating a pregnancy."
        },
        {
            "id": 13,
            "text": "The Justice findings, while not unexpected, come six months after the fatal shooting of Michael Brown, a black teenager by then-Ferguson police officer Darren Wilson, who is white."
        },
        {
            "id": 14,
            "text": "The incident prompted waves of protest across the country and a re-examination of law enforcement's relationships with minority communities."
        },
        {
            "id": 15,
            "text": "A separate inquiry into that incident is underway."
        },
        {
            "id": 16,
            "text": "That inquiry, Officials have said it is unlikely to result in charges against Wilson, who has left the department."
        },
        {
            "id": 17,
            "text": "A St. Louis County grand jury elected late last year not to indict Wilson in the shooting."
        },
        {
            "id": 18,
            "text": "Ferguson Mayor James Knowles III and Police Chief Thomas Jackson were among a contingent of city officials who met with Justice representatives Tuesday in St. Louis to receive the government's findings."
        },
        {
            "id": 19,
            "text": "\"At this time, the city is currently reviewing the report and its findings,'' said a statement issued by the city; it added that a fuller response would come Wednesday, when the complete report is expected to be disclosed.."
        },
        {
            "id": 21,
            "text": "\"This confirms what we have previously stated, that the actions of the killer of Michael Brown had to do with a systemic problem within the Ferguson Police Department,\" Benjamin Crump, an attorney for Brown's family, said of the Justice findings."
        },
        {
            "id": 22,
            "text": "\"The report shows that there were others treated inappropriately like we feel Mike Brown was treated inappropriately.\""
        },
        {
            "id": 23,
            "text": "Similar cases in other cities indicate such problems are widespread, Crump said."
        },
        {
            "id": 24,
            "text": "\"We have to work on a remedy to address this multi-city, multi-state epidemic all across America that has such adverse effects on communities of color and that is taking the lives of citizens,\" he said."
        },
        {
            "id": 25,
            "text": "Ferguson resident Iyanla Doyle, 24, said the findings confirm what she's already witnessed from living in the city."
        },
        {
            "id": 26,
            "text": "\"It's beyond sad because Michael Brown wasn't the first black male who was killed by a police officer and he's not going to be the last,\" Doyle said."
        },
        {
            "id": 27,
            "text": "\"They should look at all these police departments because everyone might be doing the same thing.\""
        },
        {
            "id": 28,
            "text": "She hopes the government will disband the Ferguson Police Department and bring in an outside agency."
        },
        {
            "id": 29,
            "text": "\"We need officers who really care about people instead of making money and locking people up,\" she said."
        },
        {
            "id": 30,
            "text": "DeRay McKesson, 29, a Minneapolis schools human relations executive who joined the Ferguson protests, agrees."
        },
        {
            "id": 31,
            "text": "\"The Ferguson Police Department shouldn't exist,\" McKesson said."
        },
        {
            "id": 32,
            "text": "\"They have proven themselves incompetent and racist.\""
        },
        {
            "id": 33,
            "text": "The report shows Wilson \"was not an exception, but he was the rule,\" McKesson said."
        },
        {
            "id": 34,
            "text": "\"Systems and structures influence the way people act."
        },
        {
            "id": 35,
            "text": "And, the systems and structures in Ferguson empowered and protected Darren Wilson.\"\u200b"
        }
    ],
